      "content": "That makes sense, putting social variables first. But for the sake of a comprehensive review, I need to address the more controversial side of the literature as well. There are some older, though still cited, studies and certain contemporary authors who suggest that these disparities in crime and even in cognitive testing outcomes aren't purely environmental, but might have underlying biological or evolutionary components related to certain racial groups. Can you summarize the arguments used by those who propose a more inherent or biological link between race and these specific behavioral or cognitive outcomes?",
